<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>JCHR control orders submission feb 06</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.5pt">VEP 0027</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written Submission by JUSTICE VEP 0027</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Voting Eligibility (Prisoners) Draft Bill </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">has been published in response to the line of European Court of Human Rights case-law which concludes that the absolute ban on prisoners voting in section 3 Representation of the People Act 1983 (“RPA”) is incompatible with the right to participate in full and fair elections. The UK is required by the European Convention on Human Rights to repeal the bar on all prisoners voting. The extended controversy over the UK’s failure to execute the judgment of the European court and the political reluctance of successive Governments to tackle this legally simple, but politically uncomfortable issue is well rehearsed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The right to vote is the very basis of democracy, is recognised in most national constitutions and international human rights instruments and has been called the ‘right of rights’. JUSTICE’s view is that, as a general rule, prisoners should be entitled to vote. Any specific restriction, if justifiable, should be considered distinct from sentence. We recognise that this is not the only option legally open to the UK. However, we regret that the options presented in the draft Bill are disappointing and contentious. Two of the options – do nothing or ban prisoners serving longer than 6 months from the ballot box – are unlawful and not rationally open to the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The third – disenfranchisement of all prisoners sentenced to over four years – bears the hallmarks of a general and automatic blanket rule which will require careful justification. While we accept that this option is most likely to be considered acceptable on review by the domestic and European Courts, we stress that it is for Parliament to consider on an evidence-based analysis whether the restriction of the franchise presents a tangible benefit for civil responsibility and the prevention of crime. We express some scepticism.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We recognise that a range of strong, sincerely held convictions about the scope of the franchise have been expressed. We hope that the publication of these legislative proposals will lead to a resolution which recognises this spectrum of opinion and the implications for the UK’s reputation of maintaining the ban, but which respects the UK’s international obligations and maintains the rule of law.</span></p><p style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; margin:0pt; padding-bottom:1pt; padding-left:4pt; padding-right:4pt; padding-top:1pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Founded in 1957, JUSTICE is a UK-based </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">law reform and human rights</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Its mission is to advance access to justice, human rights and the rule of law.  It is also the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> section of the International Commission of Jurists.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">   </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">JUSTICE has a long history of engagement with the human rights of prisoners. For instance, our 1972 report, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Living It Down</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, became the basis for the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act 1974. We also successfully represented prisoners before the European Court of Human Rights in a number of cases, including </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Weeks v United Kingdom,</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Thynne Wilson and Gunnell v United Kingdom,</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hussain v United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">On 23 November 2013, the Government published the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Voting Eligibility (Prisoners) Draft Bill</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The Draft Bill has been published in response to the line of European Court of Human Rights case-law which concludes that the absolu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">te ban on prisonsers voting in s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ection 3 Representation of the People Act 1983 (“RPA”) is incompatible with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rticle 3 of Protocol 1 ECHR, beginning in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hirst (No 2) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(2005)</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and concluding with the pilot judgment in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Greens &amp; MT </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(2010).</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">   The extended controversy over the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> failure to execute the judgment of the European court and the political reluctance of successive Governments to tackle this legally simple, but politically uncomfortable issue is well rehearsed.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">JUSTICE responded to the first consultation on prisoners voting rights in March 2007 (CP29/06)</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and again to the second consultation in September 2009 (CP6/09).</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Delay in implementation has been significantly criticised by Committee of Ministers and the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe and by the Human Rights Commissioner.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">   At home, Parliamentary Committees including the Joint Committee on Human Rights</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (“JCHR”)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the House of Commons Political and Constitutional Reform Committee have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">highlighted the issue, with the JCHR calling repeatedly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for the Government to bring forward proposals for reform.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">JUSTICE welcomes the opportunity to submit evidence on each of the options proposed by Government </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in the D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">raft Bill and the wider issues raised by the Committee’s work.  However, we deplore the significant delay in removi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ng the violation identified in s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ection 3 RPA.  We particularly regret that this issue has become politicised to the point where it may undermine the commitment of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to the international rule of law; damage the credibility of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">country</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as a diplomatic leader on democratic rights and given succour to States with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">poorer records of compliance with the minimum standards in the Convention</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We welcome the oppor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tunity for Parliament to conduct a rational, evidence-based, examination of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> how best to remove the violation of the right</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to vote currently embedded in s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ection 3 RPA.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">JUSTICE’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">view</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as a general rule</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> prisoners should be entitled to vote</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Any specific restriction, if justifiable, should be considered distinct from sentence.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  We recognise that this is not the only option </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">legally </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">open to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, we regret that the options presented in the draft Bill are disappointing and contentious.  Two of the options, in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> our view, are options which are unlawful and not</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rationally open to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  The third, disenfranchisement of all prisoners sentenced to over four years, bears </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hallmarks of a general and automatic blanket rule which will require careful justification.  While the courts may ultimately be persuaded that this option is proportionate, we</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> stress that it is the role of P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">arliament to be satisfied in the first instance that the removal of the franchise for this blanket group of prisoners serves a legitimate aim and is proportionate in all the circumstances.  We </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">raise our concern</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that this option is unduly restrictive and is liable to attract significant costs in litigation before domestic and international courts.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">raft Bill</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Government proposes three options: (a) allowing prisoners sentenced to more than either </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">four years or (b) six</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> months to vote; or (c) no change (i.e. restating the the ban in a new statute).   The Joint Committee has invited written evidence on each of these three options a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nd a range of other questions.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> JUSTICE does not address each of the Committee’s additional questions in this response, but focuses on areas in which we have expertise and experience.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">While we welcome the opportunity for Parliament to consider these measures, we note that the Committee is not due to report until after the long recess.  The Committee of Ministers has adjourned its consideration of these measures until September, in light of the publication of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">raft Bill</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the Court has continued the adjournment of around 2,500 cases against the UK until then.  When the Committee reports, the Government will then consider its response.  However,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the material accompanying the D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">raft Bill makes clear that the Government to put a range of options to Parliament when any legislation is tabled.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Prime Minister has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">made clear their own view that there should</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be no resolution to this violation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, at least</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> during this Parliament.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">   </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We hope that this pre-emption will not prevent Parliament from being offered an evidence-based solution which removes the continuing violation without delay.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">raft Bill is itself an unusual piece of drafting, clearly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">produced</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for the purposes of consultation, as opposed to detailed pre-legislative scrutiny.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, we note that the Government has not yet determined how these proposals will extend to the Devolved Assemblies.  We note that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> retains an obligation to remove the violation at issue throughout the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  A number of the cases </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">brought challenging the ban in s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ection 3 RPA have originated in Scotland </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and Northern Ireland.  T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he issue of the scope of the franchise </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in Scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is a live issue, with recent debate focused on the disenfranchisement of Scots prisoners in connection with the upcoming referendum vote.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Each of the Devolved Administrations must be actively involved in shaping the electoral law response, and we were surprised to read that this draft Bill had been published before this issue had been settled.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The right to vote, blanket bans and proportionality </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The right to vote is the very basis of democracy, is recognised in most national constitutions and international human rights instruments</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and has been called the ‘right of rights’.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">   Any interference with this right requires the strongest justification.   The presumption in any democratic State must be in favour of inclusion and universal suffrage.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Yet, while the introduction to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Draft </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Bill provides a lengthy history and chronology of the litigation involved in reaching this point, it provides little elucidation of the principles which form the basis of the current law.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he Government creates the impression that there is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">little or no bounds to the discretion afforded in circumscribing the franchise.  The only guidance given to Parliament is that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has a “wide discretion in how they regulate a ban on prisoners voting”.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">potentially</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">misleading.  A full understanding of the legal framework governing the right to vote must be the starting point for the Committee’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s work:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The right to vote is a right and not a privilege.  The right to vote </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> protected by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rticle 3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Protocol 1 ECHR</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the Human Rights Act 1998</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This right</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is not absolute, but the default favours universal suffrage, in the interests of upholding the democratic principles on which the ECHR founds:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Any departure from the principle of universal suffrage risks undermining the democratic validity of the legislature thus elected and the laws it promulgates.</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ny departure from the principle of universal suffrage must be justified in accordance with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rticle 3, Protocol 1 ECHR:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Exclusion of any groups or categories of the general population must accordingly be reconcilable with the u</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nderlying purposes of Article 3 of  the first Protocol</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="4" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Any limit on the franchise must therefore serve a legitmate aim</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and must not be a disproportionate means of meeting this aim.</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="5" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Different models are available for the organization and running of electoral systems and countries.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> wide margin of appreciation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is afforded to allow  States </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">structure the franchise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in their ‘democratic vision’.  However, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in order to be proportionate, any disenfranchisement must meet minimum standards compatible with the fundamental essence of the right to vote.</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="6" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48pt; padding-left:6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In considering the proportionality of the removal of the franchise from prisoners, it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is important to remember that “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prisoners in general continue to enjoy all the fundamental rights and freedoms guaranteed under the Convention, save for the right to liberty”.</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The removal of the franchise from a prisoner or a group of prisoners must be subject to the same rigorous proportionality assessment as from any other group:</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">There is no question…that a prisoner forfeits his Convention rights merely because of his status as a person detained following conviction.  Nor is there any place under the Convention system, where tolerance and broadmindedness are the acknowledged hallmarks of democratic society, for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">automatic disenfranchisement based purely on what might offend public opinion.</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="7" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Disenfranchisement must not be generally applicable, automatically or indiscriminately applied.</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="8" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Rather, there must be a “discernable and sufficient link between the sanction and the conduct and circumstances of the individual concerned”.</span><a name="_ftnref27"></a><a href="#_ftn27">[27]</a></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="9" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.33pt; padding-left:6.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">An independent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> judicial</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> determination in each case may help ensure the proportionality of the removal of the franchise, but such a determination is not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">necessarily </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">required.</span><a name="_ftnref28"></a><a href="#_ftn28">[28]</a></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="10" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 47.33pt; padding-left:6.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the circumstances when the franchise are to be removed are set in legislation, the legislature has a responsibility to ‘balance the competing interests in order to avoid any general, automatic or indiscriminate restriction’.</span><a name="_ftnref29"></a><a href="#_ftn29">[29]</a></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="11" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In these circumstances, these measures may yet be subject to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">judicial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">scrutiny to measure whether they are proportionate in their effects, and objectively operate to allow for a sufficient consideration of a link between the circumstances of the individual crime concerned and the removal of the vote.</span><a name="_ftnref30"></a><a href="#_ftn30">[30]</a></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Thus, contrary to the indication of the Government, guidance on the determination of proportionality</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is provided by the Strasbourg Court in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hirst (No 2)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">hile the Court reiterates that the margin of appreciation is … wide, it is not all-embracing.  Further, although the situation was somewhat impovoved by the 2000 Act which for the first time granted the vote to persons detained on remand, section 3 of the 1983 Act remains a blunt instrument.  It strips of their Convention right to vote a significant category of persons and it does so in a way which is indiscriminate.  The provision imposes a blanket restriction on all convicted prisoners in person.  It applies automatically to such prisoners, irrespective of the length of their sentence and irrespective of the nature or gravity of their offence and their individual circumstances.  Such a general, automatic and indiscriminate restriction on a vitally important Convention right must be seen as falling outside any acceptable margin of appreciation.</span><a name="_ftnref31"></a><a href="#_ftn31">[31]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">paragraph </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is confirmed in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Greens</span><a name="_ftnref32"></a><a href="#_ftn32">[32]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and again in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as clear guidance on the determination of proportionality and clearly elucidates the principles set out above</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  The Court in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">refer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">red</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to the issues set out above as the “criteria” for assessing proportionality, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">applied</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the “general, automatic and indiscriminate”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> criteria</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to assess the connection between circumstances of the individual concerned and the nature and type of the offences considered and the removal of the right to vote</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.</span><a name="_ftnref33"></a><a href="#_ftn33">[33]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It stressed:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It does not appear, however, that anything has occurred or changed at the European and Convention levels since the Hirst … judgment that might lend support to the suggestion that the principles set forth in that case whould be reexamined.  On the contrary, analysis of the relevant international and European documents…and compartative law information…reveals the opposite trend, if anything, towards fewer restrictions on covicted prisoners voting rights.</span><a name="_ftnref34"></a><a href="#_ftn34">[34]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This is clearly consistent with the guidance of the Venice Commission</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on removal of the franchise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, which provides</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that individuals may only be disenfranchised by law, when proportionate, in connection with a criminal conviction for a “serious offence”.</span><a name="_ftnref35"></a><a href="#_ftn35">[35]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Similar </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">principles govern</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the right to vote</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">protected by constitutions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> across the common law world</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  For example</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, considering the right as protected by the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms, the Canadian Supreme Court explained</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The right to vote is fundamental to our democracy and the rule of law and cannot be lightly set aside.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Limits on it require not deference, but careful examination.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> This is not a matter of substituting the Court’s philosophical preference for that of the legislature, but of ensuring that the legislature’s proffered justification is supported by logic and common sense. …  The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Charter </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">distinguishes between two separate issues: whether a right has been infringed, and whether the limitation is justified.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> The complainant bears the burden of showing the infringement of a right (the first step), at which point the burden shifts to the government to justify the limit as a reasonable limit under s. 1 (the second step).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> These are distinct processes with different burdens.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Insulating a rights restriction from scrutiny by labeling it a matter of social philosophy, as the government attempts to do, reverses the constitutionally imposed burden of justification.</span><a name="_ftnref36"></a><a href="#_ftn36">[36]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Rule of Law (Article 46 ECHR)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The continuing failure of the U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to remove the ban on prisoners voting is a violation of the United Kingdom’s obligation under </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rticle 46 ECHR to remove a violation identified by the Court.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">While s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ection 3 RPA </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">– and the bar on all prisoners voting - </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">remains in force, the violation continues.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This shows a disregard for international law which is inconsistent with the commitment of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to act compatibly with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">its</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> international obligations.  It significantly undermines the commitment of the Government to uphold international law and its capacity to expect others to respect </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to us.  As Lord Mackay of Clashfern has explained:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The [European] Convention ... was initiated ... to deal with the ... terrible persecution of minorities in Germany ... If we believe in the rule of law, we are just as much bound to observe the decisions of the European Court on matters within their competence as we are to obey the decisions of our own courts in matters within their competence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">I would just like to say that our country has embraced the rule of law for many, many generations and it still is bound by the rule of law. Therefore, when we have taken on legal obligations, as we have under the Convention of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms in Europe, the rule of law requires us to obey the courts that are set up under that Convention whose judgments are binding. I do not myself regard politics and law as, in any way, in conflict because politics in our country should be carried on under the rule of law.</span><a name="_ftnref37"></a><a href="#_ftn37">[37]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The obligation under </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rticle 46 is not simply an obligation designed to improve the law, but to avoid future violations.</span><a name="_ftnref38"></a><a href="#_ftn38">[38]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The obligation is set broadly to reflect the primary responsibility of States to effectively secure the implementation of the Convention at national level.   The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">JCHR</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has explained that taking a narrow approach to this obligation may risk further violations of the Convention and will most likely incur unnecessary public expense in litigation of issues which have been settled.  We agree with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> their concern that in responding to judgments of the European Court of Human Rights, an approach which deliberately “pushes the envelope” to challenge the scope of the law is inconsistent with the international obligation enshrined in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rticle 46 ECHR and the spirit of the Convention.  In connection with the then Government’s response to the violation identified by the Court in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Marper, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">contained in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Crime and Security Bill </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and now revisited in alternative measures in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Protection of Freedoms Act 201</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, the JCHR raised significant concerns about a limited approach to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rticle 46 ECHR:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The responsibility under Article 46 of the Convention includes the responsibility to remove the risk of future, repeat violations. In our view, the Government's decision to purposely "push the envelope" in this case creates the risk of further violations of the Convention and fails to satisfy its obligations under Article 46. In any event, even if the Government is able to persuade its colleagues on the Committee of Ministers to accept its approach, we consider that there is a significant risk that the proposals in the Crime and Security Bill would lead to further litigation both at home and at the European Court of Human Rights and a significant risk of further violations of the right to respect for private life by the United Kingdom.</span><a name="_ftnref39"></a><a href="#_ftn39">[39]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In light of the significant delay in this case, and its</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> political ramifications, it would be regrettable if a limited approach to reform were to lead to many more years of litigation on this issue before a settled position on the scope of the franchise were reached.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Options</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A continuing violation (Option (c))</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We regret that the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">included</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> an option to legislate to adopt statutory language which would broa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">dly replicate the provision in s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ection 3 RPA.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">An absolute bar on all prisoners voting will remain arbitrary, automatic and indiscriminate, bearing all the hallmarks of disproportionate disenfranchisement.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  However, there is no doubt that this option is proposed as a “do nothing” alternative.  This option is incompatible with the rule of law, and with the obligation of the U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to remove the violation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">posed by the existing blanket ban</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There has been some tacit </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">– and express – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">suggestion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">some commentators</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that the provision for this measure to be adopted in fresh legislation will somehow reinvigorate or widen the margin of appreciation afforded to the U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, by granting a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">new </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">democratic stamp of approval to the violation identified.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">JUSTICE considers that this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is an untenable reading of the law.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">consistent with the reaffirmation of the principles set out above </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by the Court in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">after the Attorney Gen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eral unsuccess</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fully argued for their revision (In the U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’s intervention, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the Government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> specifically reference</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a vote in the House of Commons on a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">motion proposed by Jack Straw MP and David Davis MP, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which supported the maintenance of the status quo, and passed with a significant majority)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> In addition, the language of both </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Greens, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in setting the direction associated with the pilot judgment, and in the Court’s variation of its timetable pending </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">makes clear that the Court considers that a legislative change will be necessary to lift the existing ban.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This would be inconsistent with a suggestion that legislating to reenact the same ban would be sufficient to meet the U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’s obligations on execution. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">his reading wou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ld depart from over a decade of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> European and international jurisprudence, consistently applied which recognises that the blanket bar on all prisoners voting is arbitrary, automatic and indiscriminate, and so disproportionate, unnecessary and unlawful.</span><a name="_ftnref40"></a><a href="#_ftn40">[40]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Similarly, this jurisprudential approach, which abhors the application of blanket and indiscriminate rule making as disproportionate and arbitrary is consistent with the wider application of Convention law.</span><a name="_ftnref41"></a><a href="#_ftn41">[41]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Removing the franchise for all prisoners according to minimum sentence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (Options (a) and (b))</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Both Options (a) and (b) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">provide for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the removal of the franchise from all prisoners serving over a specified sentence.  They vary only in the length of the sentence concerned.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">JUSTICE </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">considers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> decision to link periods of enfranchisement or disenfranchisement only to the length of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a prisoner’s custodial sentence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">undermine</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">intellectual foundation of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reasoning of Grand Chamber in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hirst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">despite the determination in that case that the Italian system was within the margin of appreciation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the Court accepted that a legislative framework might be designed with sufficient flexibility to allow for the consideration of a discernable link between the individual offender’s conduct, the nature and seriousness of the offence and disenfranchisement.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It concluded that the Italian system, which provided for disenfranchisement of offenders on a sliding scale, to be imposed from a threshold of 3 years imprisonment, was proportionate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and within the margin of appreciation afforded to Italy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  The Court reasoned:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the legal provisions in Italy defining the circumstances in which individuals may be deprived of the right to vote show the legislature’s concern to adjust the application of the measure to the particular circumstances of the case in hand, taking into account such factors as the gravity of the offence committed and the conduct of the offender. It is applied only in connection with certain offences against the State or the judicial system, or with offences which the courts consider to warrant a particularly harsh sentence.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Sentencing takes into account a broad spectrum of factors, so that two separate people charged with the same offence can be sentenced differently.  As we noted in our response to the 2006 consultation, the decision to impose a custodial sentence and its length are determined by reference to a wide variety of factors, both general in nature (e.g. deterrence, rehabilitation, protection of the public, etc) and those specific to the offence (e.g. provocation, vulnerability of the victim, etc).  Although it is true to say that the length of the sentence tends to reflect the severity of the offence, many of the considerations that attach to determining whether, and for how long, a person should be deprived of their liberty </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may have</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> little or no bearing on the question of whether a person should be liable to be disqualified from voting.   For these reasons, JUSTICE remains concerned that any policy that applies disenfranchisement as a punishment based on the length of the custodial sentence alone - without any independent assessment of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nature </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of the offence in question or any </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to support</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> determination </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">blanket </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rule</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> proposed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be considered proportionate – will clearly remain open to challenge.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Six</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> months</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (Option (b))</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Despite our principled concerns about </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the rationality of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an automatic restriction based on length of sentence, w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e consider</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that setting the bar at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">six </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">months</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> minimum sentence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would be disproportionate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  The Court in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">stresse</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that in Italy “there is no disenfranchisement in connection with minor offences”.</span><a name="_ftnref42"></a><a href="#_ftn42">[42]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  In each of the cases in which the Court’s case law is developed, emphasis is placed on the context and circumstance of the case and on the importance of distinguishing the nature and seriousness of the relevant offence.  A bar imposed on all offenders attracting a sentence of six months would cover a very broad range of offending, across a wide spectrum of types of offence.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Offences which may attract a six month sentence can include, for example, careless driving offences, shoplifting</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, lower level assaults,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> some public order </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> regulatory or environmental offences. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The prospect that the individual </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> serving a  custodial sentence of six months over a general election – likely with license, a three-month window – and will therefore be disenfranchised will be entirely dependent upon the timing of the offence, not the circumstances of the offender or the nature of the offence itself.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  JUSTICE considers that there is no interpretation of the case-law on which both domestic and European Courts are likely to consider th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at this is proportionate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref43"></a><a href="#_ftn43">[43]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Four</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> years</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">: Option (a)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> remaining </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">option is also based upon the impostion of a ban </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">starting at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">four </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">years</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> sentence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, the Court was clearly influenced by the ability in the Italian system to apply to have the franchise exceptionally reinstated outwith the ordinary rules</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, by the differentiation between offences of differing degrees of seriousness and the opportunity for securing early release and associated reinfranchisement before the completion of the original sentence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It cannot be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">simply </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">extrapolated from this analysis that any and all disenfranchisement of prisoners serving sentences over </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">three</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> years will be proportionate.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Court in that case considered a number of features of the Italian legislation including the types of offences which would attract disenfrancishement and the seriousness with which the Italian legislature could be taken to have assessed the connection between the type and nature of the offences and conduct covered by the restriction. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In these circumstances, we stress that the obligation on the Court in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was to act as a reviewing Court, allowing the domestic authorities a wide margin of appreciation.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Parliament in these circumstances to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">independent</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">consider the proportionality of a straight bar on prisoners voting based on a four year sentence, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">albeit that their decision may be subject</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">later</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> judicial consideration</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  This should be a substantive exercise, based on the requirement that any restriction to the franchise requires a high-level of justification.  It should not involve simply second guessing what might satisfy judges at home or abroad.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">JUSTICE considers that the assessment of proportionality in this case is not clear cut and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">this arbitrary bar</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> albeit set at a higher level</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and limited to more serious offences -</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may yet be incompatible with the Convention</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We note that in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hirst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and the subsequent case law, the court refers not only to the length of sentence but to the conditions and nature of the offe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ce</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the circumstances of the individual offender</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">While the Court was satisfied in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that the Italian system was proportionate, it was acting on the assumption that the domestic authorities had considered the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">range of circumstances when the franchise would be removed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> closely and had determined that only individuals convicted of serious offences </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, or those with specific offences, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would be deprived of the franchise </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In setting its own bar, Parliament will be expected to conduct this substantive exercise itself and consider whether, in effect, a four year sentence creates a sufficient link between the circumstances of all individuals sentenced within this group and their offences, and the decision to deprive them of the franchise.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In this connection, we emphasise the spectrum of offences which might attract a sentence of four years, the variation in factors which might affect sentencing guidelines and changes to sentencing guidelines which might affect legal certainty and proportionality.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Parliament is given very little information on the types of offences which attract four year sentences or the number of people serving sentences of over four years and above in the prison estate.  This is information which we would consider should be incorporated into the analysis adopted by Parliamentarians.  For example, a four year sentence was recently criticised in conn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ection with the conviction</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for public order offences </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of persons </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in connection with incitement to riot as a result of a Facebook message sent, but not acted on, during the summer riots in 2011.</span><a name="_ftnref44"></a><a href="#_ftn44">[44]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48pt; padding-left:6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We note that the Government predicts that if these measures are brought into force, 38% (just over a third) of the prison estate would be eligible to vote and would have their right to vote restored.  The Government’s figures explain that this figure is cast against the whole estate, which includes people ineligible to vote by virtue of age or nationality.   </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Parliamentarians must examine the Government’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">argument on justification closely</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Government refers to the legitimate aim of “enhancing civic responsibility and the rule of law” by sanctioning the conduct of convicted prisoners.  The Government simply refers to the acceptance of those aims as legitimate by reference to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hirst</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  However, it is the responsibility to examine not only the legitimacy of this aim, but whether the proposal is necessary and proportionate for that purpose.  This should include, in our view, an independent examination of whether the disenfranchisement of prisoners does serve the rule of law, enhance civic responsibility or prevent crime.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Others will be better placed to comment on the evidence benefits to offenders or to public protection</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, but we are s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eptical about the general deterrent effect of the deprivation of the individual right to vote.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> In addition, the benefits to civic responsibility and rehabilitation which might be involved allowing prisoners to participate in the democratic process have been emphasised by some.</span><a name="_ftnref45"></a><a href="#_ftn45">[45]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  These benefits must be balanced against any evidence that disenfranchisement is capable of having a direct impact upon the legitimate aims identified by the Government.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The assessment of proportionality should be based on clear evidence that disenfranchisement is necessary in order to provide a proportionate and tangible public good.  For example, t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he South African Constitutional Court, considering legislation to disenfranchise prisoners, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">concluded </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that a public perception of benefit is not sufficient to justify the serious infringement posed to the rights of an individual by the removal of the right to vote.  In the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">NICRO </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">case, the Court rejected the Government’s justification which was based on the need to reassure the public:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A fear that the public may misunderstand the government’s true attitude to crime and criminals provides no basis for depriving prisoners of fundamental rights that they retain despite their incarceration.</span><a name="sdfootnote44anc"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> It could hardly be suggested that the government is entitled to disenfranchise prisoners in order to enhance its image; nor could it reasonably be argued that the government is entitled to deprive convicted prisoners of valuable rights that they retain in order to correct a public misconception as to its true attitude to crime and criminals.</span><a name="_ftnref46"></a><a href="#_ftn46">[46]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We consider that the approach in Option (a) is open to a risk of further litigation and may, in our view, remain disproportionate.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Consider</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a significant sentence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">imposed on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, a young offender with no previous convictions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, in connection</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, for example</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> with a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">case of causing death by dangerous driving,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  In this connection, it may yet be a simple consequence of the timing of his or her conviction that they may be deprived of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">right to vote during the time they spend in custody</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Under the Government’s proposals there would be limited opportunity for this individual to challenge the denial of their right to vote, beyond a new Convention challenge.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Yet, this category proposed may cover a significant part of the prison population, and offences across a wide spectrum, with no opportunity for any independent consideration of the need to remove the franchise in any specific case.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Government has given the Committee – and the wider public – very little information to support its </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">case</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> We note that the information accompanying the Draft Bill invites the Committee to consider all options</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, encouraging the Committee to conduct a truly evidence based analysis of the right </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘democratic vision’ for the U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Despite our view that an alternative approach </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> be preferable, of the options proposed by the Government, it is our view that Option (a) will be the most </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">likely to be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">capable of defence before the courts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, on the basis of current case-law</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">implications of limited reform</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We outline our concerns about the implications of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">failure to remove the ban</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for the rule of law, above.  In addition, t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he right to vote recognized in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rticle 3, Protocol 1 ECHR is also recogni</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ed in the Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union.  The Charter expressly provides that where its rights reflect the language of the ECHR, its jurisprudence will act as a floor rather than a limitation on the protection offered to individual rights.  The applicat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ion of these Charter rights to s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ection 3 RPA is currently being considered by the Supreme Court in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">McGeogh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref47"></a><a href="#_ftn47">[47]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The requirements of EU law – where EU competences are engaged – will, at a minimum, require the lifting of the absolute bar on prisoner voting.  The issue has not yet been considered by the Court of Justice of the European Union.  That Court may set a higher bar for the removal of the franchise.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The majority of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> States within the Union now make some provision for the enfranshisement of prisoners, if not for full enfranchisement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref48"></a><a href="#_ftn48">[48]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  This reinforces the statement in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that the trend across Europe is towards reduced restrictions on democratic partication, given that trend is more evident within the EU than across the wider Council of Europe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The jurisprudence of the Court of Justice of the European Union has direct effect in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> law and its potential to impact further on the development of the law in this area must be borne in mi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nd by decision makers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A restrictive approach to reform is likely to lead to lengthy further litigati</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on before the domestic and Euro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an Courts, with the associated expense to the public purse.</span><a name="_ftnref49"></a><a href="#_ftn49">[49]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This short-sighted approach could be not only expensive, but counterproductive.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A failure by the U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nited </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">K</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to comply with the Convention will be subject to the political supervision of the Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe.  The sanctions open to the Committee are politically determined by the Committee, but include an option to refer the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> back to the European Court of Human Rights for a further determination and the ultimate sanction of removal of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from the Council of Europe.</span><a name="_ftnref50"></a><a href="#_ftn50">[50]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">   While this ‘nuclear option’ may seem unlikely, non-compliance will create wide-ranging practical and diplomatic impacts, which we set out below.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Comparative experience and global impacts</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Committee has asked for information on comparative experiences of prisoner voting.  We consider some of the comparative commonwealth jurisprudence above. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> We are unaware of any administrative or economic disadvantage which has come about as a result of the exercise of the right to vote by prisoners in any specific country.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">On the other hand, if the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> chooses to adopt a limited approach to reform in this case, we </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are concerned</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that it could:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Fundamentally undermine the reputation of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as a nation which respects the ECHR and the judgments of the European Court.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Undermine the obligation in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rticle 46 ECHR, by encouraging other States to take a more restrictive approach to their obligations;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Increase the burden on the European </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ourt as individuals are increasingly encouraged to resort to an international remedy as domestic authorities refuse to recognise the scope of judgments or to apply them in accordance with consistent jurisprudence;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Give succo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">u</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r to States with a higher rate of violation across the range of Convention rights who seek to use their own diplomatic process to avoid the im</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">plementation of the Convention;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.33pt; padding-left:4.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Undermine the diplomatic credibility of the United Kingdom as an important partner in the influencial Committee of Ministers, and the ability of that political body to use diplomatic leverage to drive up human rights standards across Europe. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Financial implications</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The financial implications of maintaining the status quo – or taking a limited approach to reform – are complex.  The financial impact of the global diplomatic implications for the reputation of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the credibility of the ECHR are unquantifiable.   As explained above, JUSTICE considers that each of the proposals in the draft Bill will be subject to further expensive public litigation.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As a result of the pilot judgment in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Greens, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">around 2,500 individual prisoners’ cases are stayed, pending a legislative solution.  The Court will </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">next </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">review these cases in September.  In </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Greens, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the Court awarded the applicant costs associated with his successful claim, but determined that compensation was not necessary.  The effective remedy sought was the change in the law and no further just satisfaction was warranted.  If the ban remains in place, it will remain open to the Court to reopen these cases.  In each, given the violation identified in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Hirst </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Greens </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and the absolute nature of the bar, it is likely that a determination of a violation is likely to be automatic, and the applicant likely eligible for costs.   As the delay in removing the ban runs on, the likelihood that these cases will be reopened increases.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> On the present case-law, these prisoners would not be entitled to damages.  However, the Court has in the past awarded limited damages for the denial of the right to vote and it is open to it to revisit its early determination that damages are unnecessary if the ban remains in place.</span><a name="_ftnref51"></a><a href="#_ftn51">[51]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">              </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The domestic debate</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recognise </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that people exhibit a range of strong, sincerely held convictions about the scope of the franchise.  We hope that the publication of these legislative proposals will lead to a resolution which is sensitive to this spectrum of opinion and the implications of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’s reputation of maintaining the ban, but respects the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’s international obligations and the rule of law.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t is clear that the issue of prisoners voting has provided significant cause for those voices critical of the role of the European Court of Hum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an Rights and it has fuelled a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> debate on the current system for the protection of rights in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, including through the HRA 1998.   </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e hope that the Committee will </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">conduct its work in recognition</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that this i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ssue is only one of many </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">important </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">legal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">matters</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> settled </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by the European Court of Human Rights throughout the past 60 years of its operation. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Clear case law resulting from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> cases has included</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sunday Times </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(the right to a free press without unjustifiable restriction),</span><a name="_ftnref52"></a><a href="#_ftn52">[52]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Goodwin </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(the right of journalists to protect their sources),</span><a name="_ftnref53"></a><a href="#_ftn53">[53]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Brogan </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(the right to challenge disproportionate detention without charge),</span><a name="_ftnref54"></a><a href="#_ftn54">[54]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Dudgeon </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(the lifting of the cr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">iminalisation of homosexuality),</span><a name="_ftnref55"></a><a href="#_ftn55">[55]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Halford </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(the right to privacy and freedom fr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">om unjustifiable phone-taps),</span><a name="_ftnref56"></a><a href="#_ftn56">[56]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Marper </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(overturning the blanket retention of DNA on arrest).</span><a name="_ftnref57"></a><a href="#_ftn57">[57]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Not all of these cases were politically popular at the time they were decided and they were all resisted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by the Government of the day.  However, t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he fundamental principles established by these cases are now broadly accepted as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">grounded</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the common law and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> they</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> form a fundamental part of our constitutional narrative</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Many provide the cornerstone principles of the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> jurisprudence of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ECHR.  The Convention</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> provides a fundamental set of universal human rights standards which apply across the Council of Europe, from Bradford to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Baku</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The Court has </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">around</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 8</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">00 million people within its jurisdiction and the Convention is used as leverage to improve legal and administrative standards by many, including vulnerable groups who are popularly disenfranchi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sed and socially disempowered.</span><a name="_ftnref58"></a><a href="#_ftn58">[58]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n many of these cases, the d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eterminations of the Court are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">politically and popularly condemned, including by national Parliaments.  However, the leverage of a shared minimum standard enshired in the Convention allows the Committee of Ministers to act together – using political influence and diplomatic pressure – to drive up standards and improve lives.  While some States have poor records in responding to the judgments of the Court, and many will delay for some time, we are not aware that any have expressly refused to take any steps to remove a violation once identified.  It would be exceptional if the United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Parliament, arguably the mother of all parliaments,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> were</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as a result of a clash</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> over the scope of the franchise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to inspire others </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to treat the rights protected by the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Convention </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">determined by domestic political expediency rather than shared democratic values.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">June 2013</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span></p></div><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">              </span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">(1987) 10 EHRR 293</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">(1990) 13 EHRR 666</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (1996) 22 EHRR 1.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Cm 8499</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> (No 2) </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">(App No 74025/01), 6 October 2005 (“</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst (No 2)”</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Greens &amp; MT v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">(App No 60041/08 and 60054/800), 23 November 2010.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.justice.org.uk/resources.php/217/prisoners-right-to-vote-justice-response"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.justice.org.uk/resources.php/217/prisoners-right-to-vote-justice-response</span></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.justice.org.uk/resources.php/186/prisoners-right-to-vote-justice-response"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.justice.org.uk/resources.php/186/prisoners-right-to-vote-justice-response</span></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> See the examples set out by the Joint C</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">ommittee on Human Rights in Fifteenth Report of Session 2010-12, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Enhancing Parliament’s role in relation to human rights judgments</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, paras 109 – 199.   See Nils Muižnieks, Council of Europe Human Rights Commissioner’s latest comments, condemning the decisio</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">n not to remove the ban for the purposes of the Scots Independence referendum, in May 2013, here </span><a href="http://www.holyrood.com/2013/05/european-official-condemns-voting-ban"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.holyrood.com/2013/05/european-official-condemns-voting-ban</span></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><a href="http://www.justice.org.uk/data/files/resources/217/Voting_Righs_Prisoners_UK_DCA_JUSTICE_response_1mar07.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.justice.org.uk/data/files/resources/217/Voting_Righs_Prisoners_UK_DCA_JUSTICE_response_1mar07.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> 2007 Consultation Response, para 5.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2012/oct/24/prisoners-vote-david-cameron</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> See for example, Herald, </span><a href="http://scc.lexum.org/decisia-scc-csc/scc-csc/scc-csc/en/item/2010/index.do"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Ministers fundamentalist over prisoners voting</span></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">14 May 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Explanatory Notes, para 7.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn15"></a><a href="#_ftnref15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> See e.g. the Universal Declaration of Human Rights 1948, Article 21(1) (‘Everyone has the right to take part in the government of his country, directly or through freely chosen representatives’); Article 25 of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights 1966 (‘Every citizen shall have the right and the opportunity …. without unreasonable restrictions: (a) To take part in the conduct of public affairs, directly or through freely chosen representatives; [and] (b) To vote and to be elected at genuine periodic elections which shall be by universal and equal suffrage and shall be held by secret ballot, guaranteeing the free expression of the will of the electors’).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn16"></a><a href="#_ftnref16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">'The great right of every man, the right of rights, is the right of having a share in the making of the laws, to which the good of the whole makes it his duty to submit’, William Cobbett, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Advice to Young Men and Women, Advice to a Citizen</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (1829) cited in Waldron, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Law and Disagreement</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (OUP: Oxford, 1999) p232.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn17"></a><a href="#_ftnref17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst (No2), </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 62, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 84</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn18"></a><a href="#_ftnref18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Draft Bill, Introduction, para 23.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn19"></a><a href="#_ftnref19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst (No 2), </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 59; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 82</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn20"></a><a href="#_ftnref20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst (No2), </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 62, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 84</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn21"></a><a href="#_ftnref21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Ibid.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn22"></a><a href="#_ftnref22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 84</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn23"></a><a href="#_ftnref23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 84</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn24"></a><a href="#_ftnref24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst (No2), </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 69.  The recognition of the rights of prisoners beyond the limitations on the right to liberty is clear in the common law as distinct from the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Strasbourg</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> jurisprudence.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn25"></a><a href="#_ftnref25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 69-71.  This recognition of the retained rights of prisoners during incarceration is reflected in domestic law.  As Lord Bingham explained:  Any custodial order inevitably curtails the enjoyment, by the person confined, of rights enjoyed by other citizens. He cannot move freely and choose his associates as they are entitled to do. It is indeed an important objective of such an order to curtail such rights, whether to punish him or to protect other members of the public or both. But the order does not wholly deprive the person confined of all rights enjoyed by other citizens. Some rights, perhaps in an attenuated or qualified form, survive the making of the order. And it may well be that the importance of such surviving rights is enhanced by the loss or partial loss of other rights. Among the rights which, in part at least, survive are three important rights, closely related but free standing, each of them calling for appropriate legal protection: the right of access to a court; the right of access to legal advice; and the right to communicate confidentially with a legal adviser under the seal of legal professional privilege. Such rights may be curtailed only by clear and express words, and then only to the extent reasonably necessary to meet the ends which justify the curtailment.  See </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R v. Secretary of State For The Home Department, Ex Parte Daly </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">[2001] UKHL 26</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn26"></a><a href="#_ftnref26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 82, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">paras 99-100</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn27"></a><a href="#_ftnref27">[27]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 71</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn28"></a><a href="#_ftnref28">[28]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 102</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn29"></a><a href="#_ftnref29">[29]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">ibid</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn30"></a><a href="#_ftnref30">[30]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">ibid</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn31"></a><a href="#_ftnref31">[31]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Hirst, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 82</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn32"></a><a href="#_ftnref32">[32]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Greens, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 77</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn33"></a><a href="#_ftnref33">[33]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 100</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn34"></a><a href="#_ftnref34">[34]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 95</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn35"></a><a href="#_ftnref35">[35]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Code of Good Practice in Electoral Matters, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Venice</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Commission, 2002.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn36"></a><a href="#_ftnref36">[36]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Sauvé v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Canada</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> (No.2) </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">[2002] 3 SCR 519.  See also, for example, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Chan Kin Sum v. Secretary for Justice and Another</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> [2008] HKCFI 1081</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (Hong Kong); </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Minister of Home Affairs v National Institute for Crime Prevention and the Re-Integration of Offenders (NICRO)</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> 2005 (3) SA 280 (CC) (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">South Africa</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn37"></a><a href="#_ftnref37">[37]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Fifth Report of Session 2010-12, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Po</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">litical and Constitutional Reform Committee, Voting by convicted prisoners: summary of evidence, QQs 3 and 13</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn38"></a><a href="#_ftnref38">[38]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a name="note5"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">In a number of judgments of the European Court of Human Rights has explained the nature of the obligation to abide by the Court's judgments: see e.g. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Papamichalopoulos v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Greece</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (1996) 21 EHRR 439 at para. 34; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scozzari and Giunta v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Italy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (2002) 35 EHRR 12, at para. 249; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Pisano v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Italy</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (Strking Out) [GC] App. No 36732/97, Judgment, 24 October 2002, at para. 43.</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn39"></a><a href="#_ftnref39">[39]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Fifteenth Report of Session 2009-10, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Enhancing Parliament’s role in relation to human rights judgments, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 58 </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/jt200910/jtselect/jtrights/85/8505.htm#a11"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/jt200910/jtselect/jtright</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">s</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">/85/8505.htm#a11</span></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn40"></a><a href="#_ftnref40">[40]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; vertical-align:baseline"> We are aware that the Attorney General is currently arguing before the Supreme Court that this line of case law should be ignored, in light of the domestic political approach to the history of the franchise of prisoners in the cases of Chester and McGeogh.  This is the first opportunity which the Supreme Court has had to consider this issue in over a decade, since Hirst itself.  We understand that the Government case encourages the Court to “take into account” the Strasbourg jurisprudence and then depart from it, in keeping with Section 2, Human Rights Act 1998.   We have supported a dialogue between the domestic and Strasbourg courts in the past; and this approach is envisaged by the framework of the Human Rights Act 1998.  However, it remains our view that the current law cannot support a conclusion that the original decision in Hirst is good law, or that despite the case-law in Greens and Scoppola, the current bar on prisoners voting is viable.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn41"></a><a href="#_ftnref41">[41]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal; vertical-align:baseline"> See for example, S and Marper v United Kingdom [2008] ECHR 1581, paras 118-9, 125 and Gillan and Quinton v. UK [2010] ECHR 28, paras 76 – 79.</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn42"></a><a href="#_ftnref42">[42]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, para 108</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn43"></a><a href="#_ftnref43">[43]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Scoppola, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 84</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn44"></a><a href="#_ftnref44">[44]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> See for example, Guardian, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Facebook riot calls earn men four year jail terms, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">17 August 2011  </span><a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2011/aug/16/facebook-riot-calls-men-jailed"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2011/aug/16/facebook-riot-calls-men-jailed</span></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn45"></a><a href="#_ftnref45">[45]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> For example, the Catholic Bishops have expressed their support for enfranchisement, a view based on the importance of rehabilitation.  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">A Place</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> of Redemption:  </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">A Christian Approach to Punishment and Prison</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">(2006)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn46"></a><a href="#_ftnref46">[46]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Minister of Home Affairs v National Institute for Crime Prevention and the Re-Integration of Offenders (NICRO)</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> 2005 (3) SA 280 (CC) (</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">South Africa</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">).</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">para 56</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn47"></a><a href="#_ftnref47">[47]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">George McGeogh v Lord President of Council </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">[2011] CSIH 67 on appeal.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn48"></a><a href="#_ftnref48">[48]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Members may find helpful the analysis of the treatment of voting rights across </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Europe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> prepared by the House of Commons Library together with the Foreign Office, in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Prisoners Voting Rights, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">House of Commons Library, SN/PC/01764, 15 May 2013.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn49"></a><a href="#_ftnref49">[49]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Even if some prisoners access to legal aid is further restricted, as proposed by the Government in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">, there is no requirement (at least before the ECHR) that for the purposes of pursuing a challenge that the individual must be represented.  In any event, JUSTICE reads the Government’s current proposals as subject to the exceptional funding provision in the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012, which specifically allows for funding to be within scope for challenges which engage Convention rights.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn50"></a><a href="#_ftnref50">[50]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Article 46, Protocol 14.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn51"></a><a href="#_ftnref51">[51]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> Aidan O’Neill, Evidence to the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Po</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">litical and Constitutional Reform Committee, 1 February 2011.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn52"></a><a href="#_ftnref52">[52]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Sunday Times v. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> (No. 1) (1979) 2 EHRR 245 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn53"></a><a href="#_ftnref53">[53]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Goodwin v </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> (2002) 35 EHRR 18 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn54"></a><a href="#_ftnref54">[54]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Brogan v United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> 11 EHRR 117 1988</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn55"></a><a href="#_ftnref55">[55]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">Dudgeon v </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> (1981) 4 EHRR 149</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn56"></a><a href="#_ftnref56">[56]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Halford v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (1997) 24 EHRR 523</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn57"></a><a href="#_ftnref57">[57]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">S and Marper</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> v United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> [2008] ECHR 1581</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><a name="_ftn58"></a><a href="#_ftnref58">[58]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> The range of cases which are capable of illustrating the value that the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Strasbourg Court</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> brings to bear for vulnerable and disenfranchised people, those subject to State oppression and force and their families is wide and diverse.  For example, a range of cases over the past decade which highlight the ill-treatment of the Roma community across </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">Europe</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">.  See for example, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">DH v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Czech</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Republic</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (2008) 47 EHRR 3; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Orsus v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Croatia</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> (2010), 52 EHRR 7; </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Sampanis v </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Greece</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">App no 32526//05, 5 June 2008.   </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>